`Fragments` have their own life cycle. When dealing with fragments, you always should consider they may be detached, hidden or their state was already saved.

Probably, the issue is happening because you are listen to location change events too soon. However, even if you change when you register your location listener, it is a good practice to get the `Context` (or `Activity`) in a safe way (because when detached, `Context`/`Actvity` will be null).

So, I recommend to:

    private boolean isNetworkAvailable() {
        boolean result = false;
        Context context = getContext();
        if(context != null) {
            ConnectivityManager connectivityManager = (ConnectivityManager) context.getSystemService(CONNECTIVITY_SERVICE);
            NetworkInfo activeNetworkInfo = connectivityManager != null ? connectivityManager.getActiveNetworkInfo() : null;
            result = activeNetworkInfo != null &amp;&amp; activeNetworkInfo.isConnected();
        }
        return result;
    }

`Fragment` has a `getContext()` method. So, you can replace `getLayoutInflater()` by `getContext()`

